**Microtasks** (`Promise.then`, `queueMicrotask`, `MutationObserver`) run before the next macrotask, and the whole queue is emptied each loop tick. **Macrotasks** (`setTimeout`, `setInterval`, DOM events, I/O) run one per tick. So a resolved promise beats a `setTimeout(…, 0)`:

```js
console.log('A');
setTimeout(() => console.log('timeout'));   // macrotask
Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log('promise')); // microtask
console.log('B');
// A, B, promise, timeout
```

A function bundled with references to its surrounding (lexical) scope — it keeps access to outer variables even after the outer function returns.

```js
function counter() {
  let count = 0;
  return () => ++count; // remembers `count`
}
const next = counter();
next(); // 1
next(); // 2
```

Uses: data privacy, function factories, and stable state in hooks/callbacks.

Context shares a value down the tree without prop drilling: `createContext`, wrap in a `<Provider value={…}>`, read with `useContext`.

```jsx
const ThemeCtx = createContext();
function ThemeProvider({ children }) {
  const [theme, setTheme] = useState('light');
  const toggle = () => setTheme(t => t === 'light' ? 'dark' : 'light');
  return <ThemeCtx.Provider value={{ theme, toggle }}>{children}</ThemeCtx.Provider>;
}
const useTheme = () => useContext(ThemeCtx);
```

A language switcher is the same shape (store `locale` + `setLocale`). Note its [[context-api-limitations]].

A function named `use*` that calls other hooks to package reusable stateful logic — keeping components lean and the logic testable/shareable.

```js
function useToggle(initial = false) {
  const [on, setOn] = useState(initial);
  const toggle = useCallback(() => setOn(o => !o), []);
  return [on, toggle];
}
```

Rules of hooks still apply (call at top level, only from React functions).

Split the bundle so code loads on demand instead of all upfront. In React:

```jsx
const Settings = React.lazy(() => import('./Settings'));
// render inside <Suspense fallback={<Spinner />}>
```

**Route-based** splitting is the highest-impact. Reduces the initial bundle and time-to-interactive; also lazy-load heavy components and below-the-fold assets/images.

**Jest** is the runner + assertion + mocking framework. **React Testing Library (RTL)** renders components and queries them the way a *user* would (by role/label/text), encouraging testing **behavior over implementation**.

```js
render(<Counter />);
await userEvent.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /add/i }));
expect(screen.getByText('Count: 1')).toBeInTheDocument();
```

Query by accessible role/text; avoid asserting on internal state.

- **Debounce** — run only after input *stops* for a delay (search box).
- **Throttle** — run at most once per interval (scroll/resize).

```js
function useDebounce(value, delay = 300) {
  const [debounced, setDebounced] = useState(value);
  useEffect(() => {
    const id = setTimeout(() => setDebounced(value), delay);
    return () => clearTimeout(id); // reset on each change
  }, [value, delay]);
  return debounced;
}
```

For throttle, store the last-run time in a `useRef` and skip calls inside the window.

Load the next page as the user nears the bottom. Prefer an **IntersectionObserver** on a sentinel element over scroll listeners:

```jsx
const ref = useRef();
useEffect(() => {
  const io = new IntersectionObserver(([e]) => {
    if (e.isIntersecting && hasMore && !loading) loadMore();
  });
  if (ref.current) io.observe(ref.current);
  return () => io.disconnect();
}, [hasMore, loading]);
// render list, then <div ref={ref} /> as the sentinel
```

Track `page`, `hasMore`, and `loading`; append results. For very long lists, combine with [[virtualization-windowing]].

Centralize modal state in a provider exposing `openModal(content)` / `closeModal`; a single root renders the active modal, so any component can trigger one without prop drilling.

```jsx
const ModalCtx = createContext();
function ModalProvider({ children }) {
  const [modal, setModal] = useState(null);
  const open = useCallback((c) => setModal(c), []);
  const close = useCallback(() => setModal(null), []);
  return (
    <ModalCtx.Provider value={{ open, close }}>
      {children}
      {modal && <Backdrop onClick={close}>{modal}</Backdrop>}
    </ModalCtx.Provider>
  );
}
```

Add a stack (array) if you need multiple modals; trap focus + close on Esc for a11y.

A small `useForm` hook: hold `values` + `errors`, validate against per-field rules on change/submit.

```js
function validate(values, rules) {
  const errors = {};
  for (const field in rules) {
    const err = rules[field].find(r => !r.test(values[field]))?.msg;
    if (err) errors[field] = err;
  }
  return errors; // {} = valid
}
// rules example:
const rules = {
  email: [
    { test: v => !!v, msg: 'Required' },
    { test: v => v.includes('@'), msg: 'Invalid email' },
  ],
};
```

Expose `values`, `errors`, `handleChange`, and `handleSubmit` (validate, then submit if no errors). Show each field's error inline.

Wrap protected routes so unauthenticated users are redirected to login:

```jsx
function RequireAuth({ children }) {
  const { user } = useAuth();
  const location = useLocation();
  if (!user) return <Navigate to='/login' state={{ from: location }} replace />;
  return children;
}
// <Route path='/dashboard' element={<RequireAuth><Dashboard/></RequireAuth>} />
```

Extend with role checks for authorization. Important: client-side guards are **UX only** — always enforce auth on the server/API too.

Forms whose fields are added/removed at runtime ('add another phone number') or generated from a config/schema. Keep field values in an **array in state** and map to render:

```jsx
const [items, setItems] = useState([{ value: '' }]);
const add = () => setItems([...items, { value: '' }]);
const update = (i, v) =>
  setItems(items.map((it, idx) => (idx === i ? { value: v } : it)));
```

Give each row a **stable key** (not the index if rows can reorder). Libraries: React Hook Form (`useFieldArray`), Formik.

A common machine-coding task. Fetch on mount, track `data/loading/error`, render a list, and on click set a `selected` item to show its details:

```jsx
const [data, setData] = useState([]);
const [selected, setSelected] = useState(null);
useEffect(() => {
  fetch('https://api.example.com/items')
    .then(r => r.json()).then(setData).catch(setError);
}, []);
// list:   data.map(it => <li key={it.id} onClick={() => setSelected(it)}>{it.title}</li>)
// detail: selected && <Details item={selected} />
```

Show loading + error states; debounce search or paginate if the list is large.

```css
/* 1. Flexbox — most common */
.parent { display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center; }

/* 2. Grid — shortest */
.parent { display: grid; place-items: center; }

/* 3. Absolute + transform — works for unknown size */
.child  { position: absolute; top: 50%; left: 50%;
          transform: translate(-50%, -50%); }

/* 4. margin auto — horizontal only, needs a width */
.child  { width: 200px; margin: 0 auto; }
```

Flex and Grid are the modern, preferred approaches.

Keep elapsed time in state and the interval id in a `useRef` (so it survives renders without causing them); clean up on unmount.
```jsx
function Stopwatch() {
  const [ms, setMs] = useState(0);
  const timer = useRef(null);
  const start = () => {
    if (timer.current) return;                 // already running
    const startedAt = Date.now() - ms;
    timer.current = setInterval(() => setMs(Date.now() - startedAt), 100);
  };
  const stop  = () => { clearInterval(timer.current); timer.current = null; };
  const reset = () => { stop(); setMs(0); };
  useEffect(() => () => clearInterval(timer.current), []); // cleanup
  return (<>
    <span>{(ms / 1000).toFixed(1)}s</span>
    <button onClick={start}>Start</button>
    <button onClick={stop}>Stop</button>
    <button onClick={reset}>Reset</button>
  </>);
}
```
Computing from `Date.now()` (not accumulating `+= 100`) keeps the timer accurate.

Base: a list in state with add / toggle / delete. The interview focus is **avoiding unnecessary re-renders** as the list grows:
- Memoize each row with `React.memo` so only the changed item re-renders.
- Wrap handlers in `useCallback` so memoized rows keep stable props.
- Use a **stable key** (item id, never the index if order changes).
- Update immutably; derive filtered views with `useMemo`.
```jsx
const Item = React.memo(({ todo, onToggle }) => (
  <li onClick={() => onToggle(todo.id)}>{todo.text}</li>
));
const onToggle = useCallback(id =>
  setTodos(ts => ts.map(t => t.id === id ? { ...t, done: !t.done } : t)), []);
```
Without `memo` + `useCallback`, toggling one item re-renders every row.

Define an interface, then write the logic:
```ts
interface User { id: number; name: string; email: string; }

// names of users whose email is valid
const EMAIL = /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/;
const validNames = (users: User[]): string[] =>
  users.filter(u => EMAIL.test(u.email)).map(u => u.name);

// match emails using a regex supplied at runtime (string -> RegExp)
const matchByRegex = (emails: string[], pattern: string): string[] => {
  const re = new RegExp(pattern);
  return emails.filter(e => re.test(e));
};
```
Building a `RegExp` from user input can throw on bad syntax — wrap in `try/catch` — and untrusted patterns risk **ReDoS**, so validate/limit them.

All three set `this` for a function:
- **`call(thisArg, a, b)`** — invoke now, args listed.
- **`apply(thisArg, [a, b])`** — invoke now, args as an array.
- **`bind(thisArg, …)`** — returns a *new* function with `this` (and optional preset args) fixed, to call later.
```js
Function.prototype.myCall = function (ctx, ...args) {
  ctx = ctx || globalThis;
  const key = Symbol('fn');
  ctx[key] = this;          // attach so `this` binds to ctx
  const res = ctx[key](...args);
  delete ctx[key];
  return res;
};
Function.prototype.myApply = function (ctx, args = []) {
  return this.myCall(ctx, ...args);
};
Function.prototype.myBind = function (ctx, ...preset) {
  const fn = this;
  return (...later) => fn.myCall(ctx, ...preset, ...later);
};
```

What prints, and why?
```js
console.log(1);
setTimeout(() => console.log(2));
Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log(3));
(async () => { console.log(4); await null; console.log(5); })();
console.log(6);
// Output: 1, 4, 6, 3, 5, 2
```
Synchronous code runs first → **1, 4, 6**. `await` queues the rest of the async function as a **microtask**. All microtasks (**3**, then **5**) drain before any **macrotask** (`setTimeout` → **2**). (See *Microtasks vs macrotasks*.)

Return a function that accumulates until it's called with **no argument**, then yields the total:
```js
function sum(a) {
  let total = a;
  function inner(b) {
    if (b === undefined) return total;  // terminator: sum(...)()
    total += b;
    return inner;
  }
  return inner;
}
sum(10)(20)(30)();             // 60
sum(10)(20)(30)(40)(50)(60)(); // 210
```
Each call returns `inner`, which keeps `total` alive via **closure**; the empty call ends the chain.

Recurse into any element that is itself an array:
```js
function flatten(arr) {
  const out = [];
  for (const x of arr) {
    if (Array.isArray(x)) out.push(...flatten(x)); // recurse
    else out.push(x);
  }
  return out;
}
flatten([1,2,3,[4,5,6,[7,8,[10,11]]],9]);
// [1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,10,11,9]
```
Reduce one-liner: `arr.reduce((a,x) => a.concat(Array.isArray(x) ? flatten(x) : x), [])`. For very deep arrays, use an explicit stack to avoid hitting recursion limits.

```js
// reduce (idiomatic)
const sum = arr => arr.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0);

// recursion (shows the concept)
const sumR = ([head, ...tail]) =>
  head === undefined ? 0 : head + sumR(tail);

sum([1,2,3,4]); // 10
```
`reduce` is the clean choice. Recursion demonstrates the idea but watch call-stack depth on large arrays.

Scan left to right, tracking characters seen; return the first one already seen:
```js
function firstRepeating(str) {
  const seen = new Set();
  for (const ch of str) {
    if (seen.has(ch)) return ch; // first to repeat
    seen.add(ch);
  }
  return null;
}
firstRepeating('success'); // 'c'
```
O(n) time, O(k) space (k = distinct chars). For `success`: s, u, c, c → the first character seen twice is **c**.

`createAsyncThunk` (thunk middleware) dispatches pending/fulfilled/rejected; the slice handles them in `extraReducers`:
```js
import { createAsyncThunk, createSlice } from '@reduxjs/toolkit';

export const fetchUsers = createAsyncThunk('users/fetch', async () => {
  const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/users');
  return res.json();
});

const usersSlice = createSlice({
  name: 'users',
  initialState: { items: [], loading: false, error: null },
  reducers: {},
  extraReducers: (b) => {
    b.addCase(fetchUsers.pending,   (s) => { s.loading = true;  s.error = null; });
    b.addCase(fetchUsers.fulfilled, (s, a) => { s.loading = false; s.items = a.payload; });
    b.addCase(fetchUsers.rejected,  (s, a) => { s.loading = false; s.error = a.error.message; });
  },
});
export default usersSlice.reducer;
// in a component: dispatch(fetchUsers()); read items/loading with useSelector
```
`configureStore` wires in the thunk middleware automatically.

Block `<div>`s stack vertically by default. To line them up without flexbox/margin/padding, change their **display**:
```css
.box { display: inline-block; width: 80px; height: 80px; }
/* `inline-block` flows them in a row AND respects width/height */
```
Alternatives: `display: inline` (but it ignores width/height), `float: left`, or `display: grid; grid-auto-flow: column` on the parent. Note: `inline-block` introduces small whitespace gaps from the newlines between tags in the HTML.
